{
  "query": "How does the effectiveness of altering water salinity compare to altering temperature for controlling invasive invertebrates like Asian clams and Ponto-Caspian gammarids?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both salinity and temperature alterations have been shown to effectively kill invasive Asian clams and Ponto-Caspian gammarids. For Ponto-Caspian gammarids, increasing water salinity levels killed the majority of invasive shrimp within five hours in one study, while another study found salinity increases did not kill invasive killer shrimp. In contrast, heating water to >36\u00b0C killed all Ponto-Caspian gammarids after 15 minutes exposure, and at >43\u00b0C they died immediately. For Asian clams, exposure to high salinities (18-34\u2030) achieved 100% mortality, while temperatures of 36\u00b0C or higher killed Asian clams within or after four days.",
