  "relevant_summary": "Several effective methods for controlling biofouling by Asian clams in industrial water systems have been documented. Chemical treatments have shown high efficacy, with a controlled field-based trial in Spanish irrigation systems demonstrating that fat-coated particles called BioBullets could kill 100% of the Asian clams within pipes. Laboratory studies indicate that biocides chlorine, potassium and copper are effective at killing Asian clams, with higher concentrations of chlorine and bromine delivered at higher temperatures shortening the time required for mortality. Temperature manipulation is another effective approach, with laboratory studies showing that temperatures of 36\u00b0C or higher killed Asian clams within or after four days. Mechanical removal methods have also proven successful, with suction dredging reducing Asian clam densities by 96% over two weeks in North American studies, and various dredge types in Ireland achieving biomass reductions ranging from 74% to >95% and density reductions from 65% to 95%. In Portugal, mechanical removal and regular cleaning of industrial pipes or addition of a sand filter were found to be effective methods of permanently removing or reducing numbers of Asian clams in industrial settings.",
